Part 1

Winter, 1996/97. Six months had passed since they entered their second year of MBBS.

---

The registrar's office queue moved the way government queues always move—at the pace of a man who has all the time in the world because he is not the one waiting. 

Vikram and Adarsh had been standing in it for forty minutes to submit a leave application form, a single-page document that required three signatures, two countersignatures, and, apparently, one office seal that was currently resting on the desk of a peon who had stepped out for chai and not yet returned.

Adarsh stood with his back against the compound wall, reading the same paragraph of Pharmacology for the third time. Vikram stood looking at the street outside the campus gate, doing nothing in particular.

A stray dog sat on the pavement just beyond the iron gate. It was a thin, short-haired dog, the kind that lives by the logic of government buildings—present every day, fed by no one, belonging to everyone in the way that things no one owns belong to everyone and to no one simultaneously. It was shivering, though not dramatically. A small, continuous tremble, as if its body had long ago accepted shivering as its default setting.

Vikram looked at it for some time.

Then he walked out of the gate and down the lane to the small general store near the bus stand. He came back five minutes later carrying a packet of cream biscuits—the expensive kind with the embossed pattern on the top, not the plain glucose biscuits that cost two rupees.

"You left the queue," Adarsh said.

Vikram didn't respond to this. He opened the packet, crouched beside the gate pillar, and placed the biscuits on the flat stone near the dog's feet, half a dozen of them, arranged in a loose row.

The dog looked at the biscuits.

It sniffed once, deliberately, in the formal way dogs examine things they have already decided about. Then it turned its head, walked three paces to the left, and began chewing on a torn plastic bag that had come to rest against the drainage ditch. Inside the bag, from what Adarsh could see from the gate, were some fish bones and a slick of old gravy.

The biscuits sat on the stone, untouched.

Vikram stood up, looked at the dog for a moment, and walked back to the queue.

He said nothing about it. He picked up his Pathology textbook and resumed reading exactly where he had stopped, without any visible change in expression.

Adarsh looked at the biscuits, then at the dog, then at Vikram.

"It didn't want them," he said.

"I know," Vikram said.

"Then why buy the expensive ones?"

Vikram kept his eyes on his book. "Because the cheap ones would have been for me," he said. "The expensive ones were for it."

Adarsh thought about this for the rest of the afternoon and couldn't quite find the end of it.

---

It was a cold evening, the kind where the mist rolls off the university sports ground and hangs thick around the hostel corridors. Adarsh walked down the second-floor passageway, his jacket zipped up, and knocked on the door of room twenty-four.

No answer came. He waited, then pushed the wooden door open. 

The room was empty. A single table lamp was lit, casting a circle of yellow light over the desk. On the desk lay the thick Pathology textbook, open to chapter three, the lines half-underlined in blue ink that had ended mid-sentence. 

Beside the book was a steel tumbler, full of cold tea. Vikram never left his tea unfinished; not once in the six months they had shared the room had Adarsh seen him leave a cup half-drunk. 

Adarsh noticed that small detail before he noticed anything else. It felt like a small crack in the room's normal order.

Adarsh stepped back into the corridor. The passage was quiet, the sound of television news echoing from the common room downstairs. 

He walked down toward the warden's office at the end of the block. There was only one telephone in the entire hostel—a heavy, black rotary dial phone chained to the brick wall outside the warden's window. 

Usually, there was a long line of students waiting for their turn, clutching coins and shivering in their sweaters. But tonight, the corridor was empty. 

Only Vikram stood there, his back to the staircase. He was holding the thick receiver to his ear, his head tilted down. 

He wasn't speaking; he was just listening. Adarsh slowed his steps, stopping near the concrete pillar. There was something in the way Vikram stood—his shoulders too rigid, his head bent too low.

"...when?" Vikram's voice was barely a whisper.

The telephone line crackled loudly, a distance-heavy static that filled the quiet corridor. It was a trunk call, routed through two exchanges in Cuttack and Bhubaneswar. The operator's voice cut in once—"Connected, go ahead"—followed by a loud pop and more crackles.

"...how bad?" Vikram asked. The line went dead mid-sentence, the dial tone returning in a flat, metallic hum.

Vikram stood there for a long time, the receiver still pressed to his ear, listening to the empty tone. Then, his fingers trembling slightly, he inserted his finger into the metal dial and spun it again. 

He waited, his chest rising and falling slowly. The connection clicked through. 

"...say it again," Vikram said, his voice flat. He listened to the answer for a few seconds. "I'm coming. Tonight."

He placed the receiver back on its iron hook. He didn't move; he simply stood there, staring at the grey plaster of the wall in front of him. 

The single light bulb hanging above the phone flickered once, buzzing softly in the cold air, then steadied again. Adarsh walked over, his shoes making a loud sound on the concrete.

"Vicky?"

No response.

"Vicky," Adarsh said, placing a hand on his shoulder.

Vikram turned around slowly. Adarsh had never seen his face look like that. It wasn't sad or tearful; it was completely emptied of expression, like a room where the furniture had been suddenly cleared out.

"Papa," Vikram said. He stopped there, his mouth staying slightly open.

Adarsh waited, his hand still on Vikram's shoulder.

"They said liver," Vikram continued, his voice thin. "Then the doctor said a word. I made him repeat it twice because the line was bad."

"What word?"

"Decompensated," Vikram said.

Adarsh felt his own stomach drop. He knew the word; they had read it only two days ago in Pathology, in the chapter that neither of them had finished before the exams. 

"That doesn't mean—" Adarsh started.

"I know what it means and what it doesn't," Vikram said, his voice sharp and flat. "It means nobody can tell me yet if he has one bad month or five good years. Uncle just kept saying, 'We'll see, we'll see.' I've never heard a doctor sound more useless."

Adarsh didn't know what to say. Medical college teaches you the names of diseases and the dosage of drugs, but nobody teaches you what to say to a friend whose father is dying.

"I need to go home," Vikram said, his eyes focusing on the staircase.

"I'll come with you to the station—"

"No," Vikram said, too fast. Then he looked at Adarsh and softened his tone. "No. Stay here. The semester exams are too close. I'll go alone."

"Vicky, this isn't about exams—"

"I know what it's about," Vikram said, his voice rising, then dropping immediately. "Sorry. I just need to move."

Adarsh said nothing. He followed Vikram back to room twenty-four. 

Vikram pulled a blue canvas bag from under his bed and started throwing things in—two shirts, a pair of trousers, some woolen socks. His hand went to the wooden shelf, stopping at the dissection kit. 

The small steel instruments were wrapped in a green velvet cloth, the ones he had kept wound tight and oiled since their first dissection class. He picked it up, hesitated, and then put it back exactly where it was, like leaving a marker for something to return to.

Then he looked at the open Pathology book on the desk. He held it for a second, his fingers touching the blue underlines, then closed it and left it on the table. He didn't pack it.

Adarsh noticed, but said nothing. Vikram zipped the canvas bag, the sound of the plastic teeth loud in the quiet room. 

He looked around the room once, checking the shelves and the desk, as if verifying he wasn't forgetting anything. But he was forgetting nothing; he was leaving everything.

"There's a passenger train at eleven," Vikram said, looking at the alarm clock on the desk. "I'll make it if I leave now."

Adarsh walked him down the stairs and out to the hostel gate. The night had settled fully, the campus roads dark under the eucalyptus trees. 

Crickets chirped somewhere in the bushes. A stray dog followed them halfway down the gravel path, then lost interest and curled up under a bench.

At the gate, Vikram stopped and turned to Adarsh. "If I don't come back for the practical exam next week..."

"You'll come back," Adarsh said.

"If I don't..."

"Vicky," Adarsh said, his voice firm.

Vikram exhaled, his breath turning to white mist in the cold air. "Papa always wanted a doctor in the family. He used to tell the relatives at every wedding, 'My son will wear the white coat.' Proudly. Like it was already done."

He looked down at his hands. "I don't think that's happening now."

"Don't decide anything tonight, Vicky. Just go home first."

"I'm not deciding," Vikram said. "I'm just telling you what I already know."

A cycle rickshaw turned in from the main road, its single headlight sweeping across the gate. Vikram waved his hand. The rickshaw stopped, the driver looking at the canvas bag.

Vikram picked up his bag. "Tell the professor... family emergency. I'll write a letter when I know more."

"Vicky—"

He was already climbing onto the rickshaw. He half-turned back, the yellow light of the gate lamp on his face. "Thanks for not asking if I'm okay."

Adarsh hadn't even thought to ask. There are some questions you don't ask a man carrying a bag at ten in the night because his father is dying, when nobody will tell him the truth for weeks.

The rickshaw pulled away, the driver's feet working the pedals slowly. The red tail-light shrank down the dark road, disappearing behind the trees.

Adarsh stood at the gate for a long time, the cold wind biting his neck. Then he walked back to room twenty-four. 

The door was still open, the table lamp still lit. He walked to the desk, picked up the Pathology textbook, closed it, and kept it safely inside the wooden cupboard.

It was a waiting that would take twenty-two years.

---

Vikram never came back for the practical exam. He didn't return for the next semester, or the one after that. 

His name stayed on the college register for one more year, a dry line of black ink, until it was struck off by the administration. Nobody in the hostel talked about it for long; a new batch arrived, new names occupied the rooms, and new rumors replaced the old ones.

Adarsh kept the Pathology textbook. Years later, while packing his bags to leave the hostel after graduation, he found it at the back of the cupboard. 

The blue ink lines were still there, ending mid-sentence, the dust thick on the cover. He didn't know where to send it; he had never found out Vikram's address in Cuttack. 

He kept it anyway. Every year, around the same winter week, he would open his cupboard and find the book still there, the dust a little thicker. 

He never asked himself why he hadn't thrown it out. He just closed the cupboard door again, leaving it in the dark.

[End of Part 1]
